explanation:
To decide whether any code in OS_CloseFileByName is unreachable we must understand all control-flow and side-effect influences invoked or referenced in the function: 

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: macro that may perform a pointer check and possibly return/abort; its expansion controls whether subsequent code is reachable. 
- OS_FS_ERR_PATH_INVALID: initial value assigned to return_code; needed to see whether return value assignments/updates make any branches unreachable. 
- OS_SUCCESS: compared against close_code to update return_code; needed to determine reachable value-update logic. 
- OS_ObjectIdIterateActive: initializes the iterator; its behavior (success/failure, whether it can cause early exit) affects reachability of the loop body. 
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext: loop-condition function — its return semantics determine whether the while loop body is ever entered (core to unreachable-code analysis). 
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry: invoked inside the loop and can have side effects (including altering object state or returning error codes); its behavior may affect whether later statements execute or become unreachable. 
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy: cleanup called after the loop; its behavior matters if it can longjmp/abort or otherwise alter control flow. 
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: macro/function used to obtain the stream pointer from the object table; its semantics (e.g., bounds checks, NULL returns) influence whether the dereference of stream is safe/reachable. 
- OS_stream_table: the global table referenced by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; definition/contents may determine whether an entry exists for the iterator token and thus whether the loop body is reachable. 
- OS_stream_internal_record_t: struct type of stream; required to know fields (stream_name, socket_domain) and whether accessing them is valid (affects reachability of the if/strcmp). 
- OS_SocketDomain_INVALID: constant used in the if condition; needed to evaluate if the if-condition can ever be true (affects reachability of the inner block). 
- strcmp: standard string compare used in the if-condition; its semantics are required to know whether the string comparison can succeed and thus make the inner statements reachable. 
- OS_FileIteratorClose: callback passed to OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry; its semantics (especially whether it removes the object or changes iterator state) affect whether subsequent iterations/statements remain reachable. 
- OS_object_iter_t: iterator type (contains token etc.); required to know iterator fields accessed in the function and how iteration behaves. 
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: often used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET macros to map token->index; needed to reason about validity of the table access and possible out-of-range behaviour. 
- OS_ObjectIdFromToken: used by iterator processing code (called by ProcessEntry); may affect whether processing changes object identity/state that impacts later code reachability. 
- OS_Lock_Global and OS_Unlock_Global: called by ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry (per call graph); locking/unlocking may enable/disable races or operations that change iterator results or cause aborts — relevant to reasoning about whether code after those calls remains reachable.

Collectively these symbols provide the definitions and side-effect semantics needed to determine whether any branch, loop body, or statement in OS_CloseFileByName can never be executed (i.e., is unreachable) under the implementation's actual behaviors.
